# Section D – Required Technical Simplifications

## D.1 SQLite instead of PostgreSQL + TimescaleDB

**Simplification:** All data is stored in a single SQLite file (`demo.db`). Schema is identical to the production PostgreSQL schema (same column names, types, constraints). Only the connection layer differs.

**Acceptable because:** SQLite handles 50–500 records trivially. The risk engine and trajectory logic operate on Python objects, not database-native functions. Migration to PostgreSQL is a connection-string change + Alembic migration; no logic changes required.

**Demo claim:** *"The production schema is defined. PostgreSQL with TimescaleDB is the target deployment database. For this prototype we use an identical schema in SQLite to keep the setup dependency-free."*

---

## D.2 Streamlit instead of React Web App + Android App

**Simplification:** All dashboard views (AWW form, Supervisor dashboard, Audit Trail, About) are implemented in Streamlit (Python). The Android application and React web dashboards are documented in architecture but not implemented.

**Acceptable because:** Streamlit allows functional demonstration of all data flows, role views, offline simulation, and governance screens. Evaluators are assessing logic and governance, not UI framework choice. Post-shortlisting, the Streamlit screens become the functional specification for the React/Android implementation.

**Demo claim:** *"The production interface is Kotlin/Android for AWW and React for web dashboards. This prototype uses Streamlit as a functional proxy — all data flows, role scoping, and governance logic are implemented. The production UI specification is included in our documentation."*

---

## D.3 Structured Decision Trace Log instead of Cryptographic Audit Chain

**Simplification:** Each risk computation writes a structured Python dict to a `decision_trace` table in SQLite. Fields: `{log_id, timestamp, session_role, child_id, assessment_id, tier, top_shap_feature, shap_value, is_provisional, action_taken}`. No hash chaining.

**Acceptable because:** The evaluation is assessing audit capability and governance intent. The production cryptographic chaining mechanism is documented in [ecd_system_architecture.md](file:///C:/Users/cnevi/.gemini/antigravity/brain/382a8dc0-c510-4fba-966d-20b69e5733cb/ecd_system_architecture.md) (audit_log schema with `previous_log_hash` and `log_entry_hash`). The demo log proves the system records every decision. Cryptographic integrity is a production hardening step.

**Demo claim:** *"Every risk computation and action is logged with a structured trace. Production deployment uses cryptographic audit chaining — the schema and chaining algorithm are documented. For this prototype, structured logging demonstrates the governance intent."*

---

## D.4 Manual Version Freeze instead of CI/CD Pipeline

**Simplification:** No automated testing pipeline. Engineers manually run a test suite (`pytest tests/`) before final submission. A `requirements.txt` with pinned versions replaces Docker image builds. A `CHANGELOG.md` replaces automated release notes.

**Acceptable because:** CI/CD is an operational practice, not a system capability being evaluated. The test suite still exists. The pinned `requirements.txt` ensures environment reproducibility. The evaluation committee does not run your CI/CD — they run your demo.

**Demo claim:** *"Production deployment includes automated CI/CD with container scanning and pre-deployment test gates — documented in our DevOps specification. For the prototype, we use manual validation with a pinned dependency file and documented test coverage."*

---

## D.5 Streamlit Session State instead of JWT Authentication

**Simplification:** A sidebar dropdown (`Select Role: AWW / Supervisor`) sets `st.session_state.role`. Data queries are filtered based on this value. No JWT tokens, Keycloak, or session management.

**Acceptable because:** The logical separation between roles (what each role can see and do) is identical to the production RBAC design. The enforcement mechanism is simplified. The production Keycloak RBAC configuration is documented as a deliverable.

**Demo claim:** *"Role-based access control in production is enforced via Keycloak with JWT tokens — the role configuration and permission matrix are documented. In this prototype, role logic is implemented with correct data scoping, demonstrating that the boundaries are correctly designed."*

---

## D.6 Rule-Based Offline Proxy instead of ONNX on Android

**Simplification:** When `offline_mode = True` in the Streamlit demo, the system uses a simple threshold function (not a quantized ONNX model) to produce a provisional risk tier: if the sum of indicator risk flags exceeds a domain-specific threshold, the tier escalates. This is clearly labelled `PROVISIONAL` in the UI.

**Acceptable because:** The ONNX deployment architecture is documented (quantization method, parity test criteria, Android runtime). The conceptual demonstration — "the device can produce a risk estimate without connectivity" — is fully achieved. The specific inference engine is an implementation detail.

**Demo claim:** *"On-device inference in production uses a quantized ONNX model deployed via Android WorkManager — architecture and parity test criteria are documented. In this prototype, the offline mode uses a threshold-based proxy to demonstrate the provisional-vs-canonical result flow without requiring an Android device."*

---

# Section E – Evaluation Alignment Protection

## E.1 95%+ Accuracy Threshold

**Requirement:** PoC Success Criteria requires "models with more than 95% accuracy."

**How to handle:**
- Do not report raw accuracy on a 4-class imbalanced problem. This will be misleading.
- Report and present: **Balanced Accuracy**, **High-Risk Recall (Sensitivity)**, **AUC-ROC**.
- If balanced accuracy ≥ 0.80 and High/Critical recall ≥ 0.85, your system is defensible.
- Prepare a 2-sentence explanation for evaluators: *"Raw accuracy on an imbalanced developmental screening dataset would be inflated by the majority Low-risk class. We report balanced accuracy and high-risk recall, which are the clinically meaningful metrics for this population."*
- Include this framing explicitly in the model card and the submission write-up.

> [!CAUTION]
> Do NOT claim 95% accuracy unless your balanced accuracy on the held-out test genuinely reaches that level. Evaluators will probe this. A defensible 82% balanced accuracy with 91% Critical recall is stronger than a claimed 95% raw accuracy that collapses under scrutiny.

---

## E.2 High-Risk Recall Emphasis

- Set the decision threshold for High and Critical tiers to prioritise sensitivity over specificity.
- Show the threshold sensitivity analysis chart in the submission: "At threshold X, recall = Y, precision = Z."
- In the demo, show the AWW receiving a Critical-tier alert for a pre-seeded child and being required to create a referral. This is the most powerful demo moment.
- Have the FNR figure for Critical tier ready to state verbally: *"Our system's false-negative rate for Critical-tier children is [X]%. That means [X]% of children who should have been flagged were not. We've set a 12% alert threshold with a documented rollback policy."*

---

## E.3 Longitudinal Impact Demonstration (40% Evaluation Weight)

This is the highest-weight dimension. Do not underinvest here.

- Demo must show at least one child moving from Medium to Critical over two time points.
- The trajectory chart must be visible and clearly annotated (risk transition marker).
- The cohort panel must show that the block with this child has a higher risk distribution than the control block.
- Prepare the line: *"Within a 6-month simulated cohort of 50 children, [X] showed risk tier deterioration. Our system detected these transitions automatically, enabling targeted supervisor review before the next fieldwork cycle."*
- Have the developmental coefficient number ready: *"Child ID [X] shows a cognitive developmental coefficient of [−0.8 SD], meaning they are tracking 0.8 standard deviations below their age cohort mean — this triggered automatic escalation."*

---

## E.4 Screening-Level Boundary

- The disclaimer must appear on every risk result screen, in the colour-code border: *"This is a developmental screening flag, not a clinical diagnosis. All High and Critical flags require supervisor review and referral to a qualified health professional."*
- The referral widget must be the visual proof of this boundary: the system does not act — the AWW acts.
- If asked: *"Where does the AI make the decision?"* — the answer is: *"The AI makes no decision. It produces a probability-calibrated risk tier. The AWW must select an action. The Supervisor confirms referrals. The system is a decision support layer, not a decision-making system."*

---

## E.5 DPDP Compliance Narrative

Three specific points to demonstrate in the demo:
1. **Consent first:** Show that the AWW cannot submit an assessment without completing the consent form for that child. This is enforced in the UI flow.
2. **Minimal data:** Show the indicator list. Every field has a one-line justification in the Data Dictionary. *"We collect only what is necessary for screening. The data minimisation audit is in our documentation."*
3. **Government ownership:** Show the "About This System" page. The data ownership statement reads: *"All data is stored on government-controlled infrastructure. The vendor has no access to child data. The system is designed for full government ownership at handover."* This is a 5-second display moment that registers strongly with evaluators.

---

## E.6 Government Ownership Positioning

- In the demo and Q&A, use the phrase *"government-controlled infrastructure"* not *"our servers."*
- When asked about hosting: *"The target deployment environment is NIC Data Centre or State Data Centre — whichever the state government designates. We have no proprietary lock-in. The deployment stack is fully documented in our infrastructure specification."*
- Point to the architecture document if pressed: it includes the DB schema, API structure, and Docker Compose starting configuration.

---

# Section F – Verification & Review Checklist

## F.1 Pre-Submission Validation Checklist

### Functional
- [ ] AWW screening form: accepts full record, validates age-band, returns risk tier — tested with 5 different children
- [ ] Risk result shows tier badge + top-3 SHAP labels + disclaimer text — verified for all 4 tier levels
- [ ] Disclaimer text on every result screen — visual check each screen
- [ ] Supervisor dashboard: loads all 50 demo children; sortable; referral flags visible — confirmed
- [ ] Trajectory chart: renders correctly for children with 1 time point (graceful message) and 2+ time points (chart) — tested both
- [ ] Risk transition: Medium→Critical transition correctly annotated on trajectory chart — confirmed
- [ ] Cohort panel: tier distribution bar chart correct vs. actual DB records — spot-checked 10 records
- [ ] Consent form: record written to DB; consent field required before assessment — confirmed
- [ ] Decision trace log: one entry per risk computation; correct fields — confirmed for 5 test runs
- [ ] Offline simulation: toggle disables DB calls; provisional tier returned; SHAP placeholder shown — confirmed
- [ ] Referral widget: appears on High/Critical; blocks navigation until action selected — confirmed on Critical test child
- [ ] Role scoping: AWW session cannot query Supervisor-scope children — confirmed with query inspection

### Data Integrity
- [ ] All 50 demo children have at least 1 assessment and 1 risk result — SELECT COUNT verified
- [ ] All 10 trajectory demo children have ≥ 2 time points — verified
- [ ] 3 pre-seeded demo trajectories (stable, improving, deteriorating) render as expected — visual check
- [ ] No null tiers in `risk_results` table — `SELECT COUNT(*) WHERE overall_tier IS NULL = 0`
- [ ] Consent records exist for all 50 demo children — verified

### Documentation
- [ ] `model_card_v1.md` contains real metric values (not placeholder text) — reviewed
- [ ] `bias_report_v1.md` contains disaggregated AUC and FNR by gender — reviewed
- [ ] Calibration plot PNG generated from actual model output — confirmed
- [ ] DPDP compliance one-pager maps every requirement to a control — reviewed

