## F.3 Likely Expert Review Questions & Prepared Answers

| Question | Prepared Answer |
|---|---|
| "What is your model's accuracy?" | "Balanced accuracy is [X]% on our synthetic held-out test set. High-risk recall is [Y]%, meaning [Y]% of children who needed flagging were identified. Full metrics are in our model card." |
| "How do you handle false negatives?" | "We set an asymmetric decision threshold favouring recall for High and Critical tiers. A 12% FNR alert threshold is documented with a model rollback policy. The FNR on our test set is [X]%." |
| "Is this a diagnosis tool?" | "No. It is a screening-level decision support tool. The system cannot and does not produce a clinical diagnosis. Every result shows an explicit disclaimer. The AWW must take an action; the system does not act autonomously." |
| "What happens after a child is flagged?" | "The AWW must select a referral action before the screen can be dismissed. The referral is logged. In the target architecture, the PHC outcome is captured to provide ground-truth labels for model retraining. The full referral feedback loop is documented." |
| "Where is the data stored?" | "On government-controlled infrastructure. In production, NIC or State Data Centre. In this prototype, a local SQLite file that would be replaced by PostgreSQL on the government server. No data leaves the government network." |
| "How does this work offline?" | "The Android app — documented in our architecture — uses a quantized ONNX model stored on-device to produce a provisional risk tier without connectivity. In this prototype, we demonstrate the offline logic with a simulation. The full ONNX deployment specification is in our architecture document." |
| "Who has access to the data?" | "Access is role-scoped. AWWs see only their anganwadi's children. Supervisors see their block. CDPOs see their district. In production, this is enforced via Keycloak RBAC. In this prototype, the scoping logic is implemented via query filters." |
| "How do you ensure the model doesn't discriminate?" | "We run disaggregated metrics by gender and geography. The bias report is in our submission. We've documented a retraining trigger if performance disparity across groups exceeds 5%. Current synthetic-data results show no significant disparity — [cite figures from bias report]." |
| "How do you know the model will work on real data?" | "We don't yet — and we say so explicitly. Our model is trained on validated synthetic data. We've designed a Shadow Deployment Mode: the model runs silently on real data for 4 weeks before results are shown to AWWs, with a government sign-off gate before activation. The protocol is documented." |
| "What is the 5-year plan?" | "Phase 8 of our development plan covers the full 5-year O&M lifecycle: annual retraining, security audits, technology refresh, and government knowledge transfer. The plan includes a cost model at approximately ₹1.41 per child screened per year at full scale." |

